                     Such a one will not giue, lest his white hand

should touch the poore beggars: who perhaps
hath a hand cleaner then his; I meane, from aspersions
of bloud, rapine, iniury, briberie, lust
and filthinesse. He cannot intend to pray; for
he is called to dinner iust when his last locke is
hung to his minde. O the monstrous curiositie
of tricking vp this earth of earth! yet from the
Courtier to the Carter, from the Lady to the
Inkle-beggar,* there is this excesse and going beyond
their calling.
                     But I haue strayed out of my way, to cut off
a lappe of Prides garment: I conclude this Earth
with this caution. Respice, aspice, prospice. Looke
back what thou wast: behold what thou art: consider
what thou must be.BERNARD 
